  "prompt": "What does add on item on Amazon mean?",
  "response": "An \"Add-on item\" on Amazon refers to a product that can only be purchased if the total order value meets a certain minimum threshold, usually set by Amazon. This feature was introduced to make it more convenient for customers to have small, inexpensive items shipped with larger orders, thereby reducing the number of separate shipments and potentially saving on shipping costs.\n\nHere are some key points about Add-on items:\n\n1. **Minimum Order Value**: To purchase an Add-on item, your total order must meet the minimum purchase requirement, which can vary but is often around $25 or more.\n\n2. **Prime Membership**: Add-on items are generally available only to Amazon Prime members. Non-Prime members cannot purchase these items.\n\n3. **Eligible Products**: Add-on items are typically low-cost, small-sized products like certain groceries, household items, or personal care products.\n\n4. **Checkout Process**: During checkout, if your order total doesn't meet the minimum required to include an Add-on item, you will be prompted to add more items to your cart.\n\n5. **Purpose**: The primary purpose of Add-on items is to encourage larger orders, which can benefit both Amazon (by reducing shipping costs) and customers (by consolidating multiple small purchases into one shipment).\n\nIf you're interested in purchasing an Add-on item, make sure your cart's total value meets the necessary threshold before proceeding to checkout.",
